API Methods
1. log() — log one event
Use log() when you need to write a single informational or operational event immediately.
This is the best method for:

one-off process events
coding or imputation step notes
manual review routing messages
step completion / status events
simple row-level events emitted inline


Signature (conceptual)

logger.log(
    *,
    event_type,
    message,
    rule_name=None,
    response_id=None,
    case_id=None,
    variable_name=None,
)


Parameters
event_type (required)
Type/category of event.
Examples:

coding
imputation
validation
review
manual_intervention

This field helps downstream filtering and grouping.

message (required)
Human-readable description of what happened.
Examples:

Applied coding rule successfully
DOB imputed using age distribution
Record flagged for manual review

This is required because events are intended to be human-readable operational records.

rule_name (optional)
Specific business/process rule associated with the event.
Examples:

ethnic_group_coding_v1
dob_imputation_v2
manual_review_routing_rule

Unlike ExceptionLogger’s rule, this is free text and is not registry-controlled.

response_id (optional)
Identifier of the row/record being observed.
Examples:

person_nbr
dwell_nbr

Optional because some events may be task-level rather than row-level.

case_id (optional)
Case identifier associated with the event.
Use when available (for example Salesforce case id).

variable_name (optional)
Name of the variable involved in the event.
Examples:

i_age
i_mode
ethnic_group

Use when the event is tied to one variable.

Example

logger.log(
    event_type="coding",
    message="Applied ethnic group coding rules successfully",
    rule_name="ethnic_group_coding_v1",
    response_id="P12345",
    case_id="500Mp00000d56UCIAY",
    variable_name="ethnic_group",
)


2. log_dataframe() — bulk logging from a Spark DataFrame
Use log_dataframe() when you have a Spark DataFrame where each row represents one event to log.
This is the best method for:

row-level imputation outcomes
manual review routing results
bulk processing notes attached to many rows
any event already represented in a DataFrame


Signature (conceptual)

logger.log_dataframe(
    df,
    *,
    event_type,
    rule_name=None,
    rule_name_column=None,
    message=None,
    message_column=None,
    response_id_column,
    case_id_column=None,
    collection_instance_id_column=None,
    variable_name=None,
    variable_name_column=None,
)


Required parameters
df (required)
Spark DataFrame containing one row per event to be logged.

event_type (required)
Event category applied to every row.
Examples:

coding
imputation
review
validation


response_id_column (required)
Name of the DataFrame column containing response IDs for each row.
Examples:

"person_nbr"
"dwell_nbr"

This is required because bulk event logging is row-scoped.

message or message_column (required: exactly one)
You must provide one of:

message — one constant message applied to every row
message_column — a DataFrame column containing per-row message text


Optional per-row column parameters
rule_name_column (optional)
Name of the DataFrame column containing per-row rule names.
Use when each row has a different rule/process name.
Example values inside the column:

dob_imputation_v1
coding_rule_a
manual_review_routing


case_id_column (optional)
Name of the DataFrame column containing case IDs.
Example:

"i_id"


collection_instance_id_column (optional)
Name of the DataFrame column containing collection instance IDs.
If provided:

per-row values are written

If omitted:

logger uses the default context value from for_task(...)


variable_name_column (optional)
Name of the DataFrame column containing per-row variable names.
Use when:

the DataFrame spans multiple variables

Example values inside the column:

i_age
i_mode
i_dob_year


Optional constant parameters
rule_name (optional)
Constant rule name applied to every row.
Use this when the entire DataFrame relates to the same process/business rule.
Mutually exclusive with:

rule_name_column


message (optional alternative to message_column)
Constant message applied to every row.
Mutually exclusive with:

message_column


variable_name (optional)
Constant variable name applied to every row.
Use when the entire DataFrame relates to one variable.
Mutually exclusive with:

variable_name_column


Mutual exclusivity rules
Do not pass both of the following pairs together:

message and message_column
rule_name and rule_name_column
variable_name and variable_name_column

If both are passed, the logger raises ValueError.

Common shapes of log_dataframe()
A. Constant message, constant rule name
Use this when:

all event rows are the same kind of event
one message describes all rows
one rule/process name describes all rows


logger.log_dataframe(
    df_imputed,
    event_type="imputation",
    rule_name="dob_imputation_v1",
    message="DOB imputed using age distribution",
    response_id_column="person_nbr",
    case_id_column="i_id",
    variable_name="i_dob_year",
)



B. Per-row message
Use this when:

each row has its own message text

logger.log_dataframe(
    df_events,
    event_type="review",
    message_column="event_message",
    response_id_column="person_nbr",
    case_id_column="i_id",
)



C. Per-row message + per-row rule name
Use this when:

each row may be explained by a different rule/process

logger.log_dataframe(
    df_events,
    event_type="review",
    message_column="event_message",
    rule_name_column="rule_applied",
    response_id_column="person_nbr",
    case_id_column="i_id",
    variable_name_column="variable_name",
    collection_instance_id_column="collectionInstance",
)


D. Per-row collection instance override
Use this when:

one DataFrame spans multiple collection instances


logger.log_dataframe(
    df_events,
    event_type="coding",
    message_column="msg",
    response_id_column="person_nbr",
    collection_instance_id_column="collectionInstance",
)


How records are built
For each event record, the logger writes:
Framework-managed

id
created_timestamp_utc

Run/task context

run_id
task_key
source_table
target_table

Caller/data-driven

event_type
rule_name
message
response_id
case_id
collection_instance_id
variable_name


Buffering and flushing
How buffering works
The logger stores records in memory until:

buffer reaches batch_size
flush() is called
the context manager exits

Why use a context manager
Using:

with EventLogger.for_task(...) as logger:
    …


ensures:

buffered rows are flushed automatically at the end of the block
you don’t accidentally leave unwritten rows in memory


Running in different environments
Option 1 — override the log table path
Use this when writing to a different catalog/schema/table:


with EventLogger.for_task(
    spark=spark,
    log_table_path="socpophousdata1_tst.social_census_logs.events",
) as logger:
    …



Option 2 — use environment variable
Set:
CENSUS_EVENT_LOG_TABLE
Then EventLogger.for_task(...) will pick that up automatically.

Table creation / migration
Before using the logger in a new environment, run:

src/utils/logger/create_log_tables.sql


If the table schema does not match the logger schema, construction fails with:

TableContractError


Troubleshooting
TableContractError: schema mismatch
Cause
The deployed Delta table schema does not match the logger schema.
What to check

Does the table have id instead of observation_id?
Has job_id been removed?
Is case_id present?
Is collection_instance_id present?

Fix

Apply the latest create_log_tables.sql
Or migrate the table schema


No logs written to the table
Possible causes

logger buffer was never flushed
not using a with block
write failure occurred and was raised

Fix

use a context manager
or call flush() explicitly


ValueError: every event needs a message
This occurs when log_dataframe() is called without:

message
and without message_column

Fix
Provide exactly one of:

message
message_column


ValueError: not both
This occurs when mutually exclusive arguments are supplied together.
Common examples

message + message_column
rule_name + rule_name_column
variable_name + variable_name_column

Fix
Choose either:

a constant value
or a per-row column


rule_name not appearing as expected
If each row has a different rule/process name, use:

rule_name_column

If every row has the same rule/process name, use:

rule_name


Best practices

Use log() for one-off operational events
Use log_dataframe() when events are already available in a Spark DataFrame
Avoid logging every successful row unless it adds real business value
Prefer aggregated or meaningful row-level events over log explosion
Use rule_name_column when different rows correspond to different rules
Use case_id when available for Salesforce correlation
Use collection_instance_id_column when DataFrame rows span multiple collection instances
Always use a context manager for automatic flush
